---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Text from "@/components/fundations/elements/Text.astro";
import Wrapper from "@/components/fundations/containers/Wrapper.astro";
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Copyright Guide"
  description="How the UI Collective handles copyright and infringement claims, with steps for external parties and a reference for classifying common scenarios."
  pageType="webpage"
>
  <section>
    <Wrapper variant="standard" class="py-12">
      <Text
        tag="h1"
        variant="textBase"
        class="text-foreground font-medium text-balance"
      >
        Guide to Copyright &amp; Infringement Claims
      </Text>

      <Wrapper variant="prose" class="mt-2 pt-2 border-t border-border">
        <h3>How We Handle Claims</h3>

        <h4>Claims against members</h4>
        <p>
          For concerns involving fellow members, follow the dispute resolution
          process outlined in the <a href="/collective-charter">Charter</a> —
          private resolution first, then facilitated discussion, then collective
          review if needed.
        </p>

        <h4>Claims against external parties</h4>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Wait 24 hours.</strong> When we see our work copied,
            it&apos;s easy to react emotionally. If you just discovered the
            issue, give yourself time before acting.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Check your assumptions.</strong> Could this be coincidence,
            convergent design, or a shared reference?
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Assess the illegality.</strong> Use the classification table
            below. If it falls in the &quot;generally legal&quot; range, consider
            whether a claim is worth the effort. Claims against &quot;generally
            legal&quot; issues will typically be enforced using public shaming and
            reputation damage.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Gather evidence.</strong> Before making any claim, document
            everything. Take screenshots, archive URLs, save code comparisons, and
            record timestamps. This is critical — once a claim is made, bad
            actors will often attempt to sanitize their work by removing,
            altering, or redeploying the infringing material. Your evidence needs
            to be captured before they know you&apos;re looking.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Present your concern clearly and professionally.</strong> Any
            claim should include:
            <ul>
              <li>What was allegedly copied (with links or screenshots).</li>
              <li>
                What the original work is (with links or proof of prior
                publication).
              </li>
              <li>
                Why you believe this goes beyond legitimate inspiration.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Take action.</strong> Members may enforce their rights
            independently at any time. When doing so:
            <ul>
              <li>
                Conduct all formal communications in writing — email, platform
                messages, or legal notices.
              </li>
              <li>
                Save copies of all correspondence. If communicating through a
                platform, screenshot the messages in case they are deleted.
              </li>
              <li>
                If seeking Collective assistance, this documentation is what
                enables the membership to assess the situation and respond
                effectively. Follow the process outlined in the Charter —
                provide your documentation, allow the Collective to assess, and
                support a proportional response.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Request Collective assistance.</strong> If individual
            enforcement has been insufficient, or the issue affects multiple
            members, bring it to the Collective. Your documentation from the
            previous steps is what enables the membership to act. The Collective
            will review your case and decide on a proportional response, which may
            include:
            <ul>
              <li>Advice and strategy on next steps.</li>
              <li>
                A coordinated private communication to the external party.
              </li>
              <li>
                A coordinated public statement on behalf of the membership.
              </li>
              <li>
                Platform reporting on behalf of multiple affected members.
              </li>
              <li>Shared legal resources or legal referral.</li>
              <li>
                No collective action, if the evidence does not warrant it or the
                matter is better handled individually.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ol>

        <hr />

        <h3>Common Scenarios &amp; How They&apos;re Classified</h3>
        <p>
          The following is a reference guide for evaluating copyright and
          infringement claims. Not every situation is black and white — context,
          degree, and intent all matter.
        </p>

        <h3>Clearly Illegal</h3>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Scenario</th>
              <th>Classification</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Breaking the terms of a license</strong></td>
              <td>Illegal. Always considered infringement.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <strong>Reselling a purchased template/code as-is</strong>
              </td>
              <td>
                Illegal. Buying a competitor&apos;s template and selling it
                unchanged.
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Likely Illegal / Unethical</h3>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Scenario</th>
              <th>Classification</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <strong
                  >Slightly modifying a purchased template and reselling</strong
                >
              </td>
              <td>
                Likely illegal / unethical. Changing a few colors or images and
                marketing it as your own.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <strong
                  >Using AI to remix purchased template/code and reselling</strong
                >
              </td>
              <td>
                Likely illegal / likely unethical. Inputting competitor code into
                AI, tweaking the output, and selling it. The use of AI as an
                intermediary does not change the underlying obligation to respect
                licenses and intellectual property. If the output is substantially
                derived from the input, it is treated the same as manual copying.
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Legal Gray Area</h3>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Scenario</th>
              <th>Classification</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <strong>Replicating a layout or design pattern exactly</strong>
              </td>
              <td>
                Legal / ethically gray. Coding your own version of someone&apos;s
                layout or section structure. Common in practice, but the closer the
                replication, the more it strains community standards.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <strong>Replicating a design and using the same assets</strong>
              </td>
              <td>
                Likely illegal / unethical. Using the same images, illustrations, or
                licensed assets as the original crosses from inspiration into
                potential infringement.
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Generally Legal / Depends on Degree</h3>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Scenario</th>
              <th>Classification</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <strong
                  >Inspiration — copying designs with an original spin</strong
                >
              </td>
              <td>
                Legal / likely ethical / widely practiced. Screenshotting a section
                or layout, coding it with different assets, colors, and styling.
                The degree of difference matters.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <strong>Reselling open-source templates with minor changes</strong>
              </td>
              <td>
                Legal / unethical. Taking an open-source UI kit, rebranding it,
                and selling with minimal changes.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <strong>Reselling open-source templates with major changes</strong>
              </td>
              <td>
                Legal / likely ethical. Significantly modifying layout, styling, or
                components before selling.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <strong
                  >Aggregating/distributing open-source work without adding value</strong
                >
              </td>
              <td>
                Legal / could be distasteful. Bundling many open-source templates
                without improvement to drive traffic or profit.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <strong
                  >Aggregating/distributing open-source work with added value</strong
                >
              </td>
              <td>
                Legal / ethical. Curating templates, adding components, optimizing
                UX, or creating a cohesive library.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <strong
                  >Shipping work produced by a contractor that contains infringement</strong
                >
              </td>
              <td>
                Depends on response. The member is responsible for work published
                under their name, regardless of who produced it. What matters is how
                the member responds when the issue is identified — prompt removal
                and good-faith resolution preserve standing.
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Keep In Mind</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Legality and ethics are not the same thing.</strong> Something
            can be legal but still violate the standards of this community.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Similarity alone is not infringement.</strong> When assessing
            whether work has been copied, degree matters. Many designs in this
            industry look similar — that is a reality of working within shared
            frameworks, trends, and conventions. The further someone moves from
            the original in design, code, and assets, the more defensible their work
            becomes. If your concern does not fall in the &quot;clearly illegal&quot;
            category, be honest with yourself about whether what you&apos;re
            seeing is actual infringement or a similar design.
            <p>
              However, similar-looking designs can still have illegal origins. Ask
              whether the work was built from your source code or files — if so,
              the provenance involves infringement regardless of how different the end
              result looks. Also consider scale: if you see hundreds of similar
              designs appearing in a short timeframe, particularly with signs that AI
              was used to remix your code, that pattern is worth investigating and
              documenting before bringing it to the Collective.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Intent reveals character.</strong> Most creators in this space
            can recognize the difference between a genuine mistake and a deliberate
            grift. When concerns are raised, a good-faith actor will engage,
            cooperate, and make it right. Bad actors will deny, deflect, go silent,
            or dismiss the concern entirely. We evaluate not just what happened, but
            how someone responds when it&apos;s brought to their attention.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong
              >Emotional reactions are understandable but can backfire.</strong
            >
            When you discover what appears to be a copy of your work, the instinct to
            react publicly and immediately is natural. But we have seen cases where
            emotional public responses turned out to be wrong — and those responses
            carry real risk, both legally and reputationally, for the person making
            the claim. This should not discourage you from pursuing legitimate
            concerns. But if you approach the situation calmly, assume best
            intentions, and lead with evidence rather than accusations, your
            outcomes will be better — even if your claim ultimately turns out to be
            unfounded. A measured response protects your credibility whether
            you&apos;re right or wrong.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </Wrapper>
    </Wrapper>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
